1
00:00:30,113 --> 00:00:33,033
You are gonna love this!
One, two, three.

2
00:00:33,951 --> 00:00:36,161
-Hmm!
-Ah!

3
00:00:36,245 --> 00:00:37,704
It's lovely.

4
00:00:41,375 --> 00:00:43,126
You want to buy Shukina?

5
00:00:46,547 --> 00:00:49,800
TRADER: Peshwami? Most beautiful
Peshwami in all of Shan Shen.

6
00:00:49,883 --> 00:00:51,760
Oh, no. Thanks.

7
00:01:01,186 --> 00:01:03,021
Tell your fortune, lady?

8
00:01:03,105 --> 00:01:06,567
The future predicted.
Your life foretold.

9
00:01:06,650 --> 00:01:08,402
Oh, no thanks.

10
00:01:08,485 --> 00:01:11,863
Don't you want to know
if you're going to be happy?

11
00:01:13,156 --> 00:01:15,242
I'm happy right now, thanks.

12
00:01:15,325 --> 00:01:19,496
You got red hair.
The reading's free for red hair.

13
00:01:20,289 --> 00:01:21,790
All right, then.

14
00:01:34,177 --> 00:01:36,597
Oh, you're fascinating.

15
00:01:36,680 --> 00:01:39,349
No, but you're good.

16
00:01:39,433 --> 00:01:40,976
I can see

17
00:01:41,059 --> 00:01:42,853
d man.

18
00:01:42,936 --> 00:01:45,939
The most remarkable man.

19
00:01:46,023 --> 00:01:49,443
-How did you meet him?
-You're supposed to tell me.

20
00:01:49,526 --> 00:01:51,486
I see the future.

21
00:01:51,570 --> 00:01:53,322
Tell me the past.

22
00:01:53,405 --> 00:01:55,741
When did your lives cross?

23
00:01:56,825 --> 00:01:58,702
It's sort of complicated.

24
00:01:58,827 --> 00:02:01,496
I ended up in his spaceship
on my wedding day.

25
00:02:01,580 --> 00:02:05,667
-Long story.
-But what led you to that meeting?

26
00:02:05,751 --> 00:02:08,128
All sorts of things.

27
00:02:08,587 --> 00:02:11,048
But my job, I suppose.

28
00:02:11,131 --> 00:02:14,760
It was on Earth,
this planet called Earth. Miles away.

29
00:02:14,843 --> 00:02:17,387
But I had this job, as a temp.

30
00:02:17,512 --> 00:02:20,515
I was a secretary
at a place called HC Clements.

31
00:02:21,808 --> 00:02:24,227
WOMAN: HC Clements. Can I help you?

32
00:02:26,188 --> 00:02:27,606
Oh...

33
00:02:29,316 --> 00:02:32,069
-Sorry.
-It's the incense.

34
00:02:32,778 --> 00:02:35,322
Just breathe deep.

35
00:02:37,074 --> 00:02:40,744
This job of yours,
what choices led you there?

36
00:02:42,496 --> 00:02:45,999
There was a choice. Six months before.

37
00:02:46,541 --> 00:02:49,753
'Cause the agency offered me
this contract at HC Clements.

38
00:02:50,754 --> 00:02:53,256
DONNA: There was this other job.
My mum knew this man.

39
00:02:53,382 --> 00:02:55,676
SYLVIA: Jival, he's called.

40
00:02:55,759 --> 00:02:57,761
Jival Chowdry.

41
00:02:58,845 --> 00:03:03,308
He runs that little photocopy business
and he needs a secretary.

42
00:03:03,392 --> 00:03:05,143
I've got a job.

43
00:03:05,227 --> 00:03:07,604
As a temp. This is permanent.

44
00:03:07,688 --> 00:03:10,065
It's 20,000 a year, Donna.

45
00:03:10,148 --> 00:03:13,110
HC Clements is in the City.

46
00:03:13,193 --> 00:03:16,863
It's nice, it's posh, so stop it.

47
00:03:20,242 --> 00:03:23,870
Your life could have gone
one way or the other.

48
00:03:24,705 --> 00:03:26,623
What made you decide?

49
00:03:26,707 --> 00:03:28,250
I just did.

50
00:03:28,333 --> 00:03:31,545
But when was the moment?
When did you choose?

51
00:03:34,631 --> 00:03:37,050
It won't take long. Just turn right.

52
00:03:37,134 --> 00:03:40,637
We'll pop in and see Mr Chowdry,
so Suzette can introduce you.

53
00:03:40,721 --> 00:03:43,724
I'm going left.
If you don't like it, get out and walk.

54
00:03:43,807 --> 00:03:48,186
If you turn right, you'll have a career,
not just filling-in.

55
00:03:48,270 --> 00:03:49,855
You think I'm so useless.

56
00:03:49,938 --> 00:03:53,191
Oh, I know why you want a job
with HC Clements, lady.

57
00:03:53,275 --> 00:03:55,235
'Cause you think you'll meet a man

58
00:03:55,318 --> 00:03:58,155
with lots of money
and your whole life will change.

59
00:03:58,238 --> 00:04:02,117
Well, let me tell you, sweetheart,
City executives don't need temps.

60
00:04:02,200 --> 00:04:04,161
Except for practice.

61
00:04:05,871 --> 00:04:08,331
Yeah. Well, they haven't met me.

62
00:04:10,709 --> 00:04:13,003
FORTUNE TELLER: You turned left.

63
00:04:13,628 --> 00:04:16,965
But what if you'd turned right?
What then?

64
00:04:17,966 --> 00:04:20,343
-Let go of my hands.
-What if it changes?

65
00:04:20,469 --> 00:04:24,264
What if you go right?
What if you could still go right?

66
00:04:29,978 --> 00:04:31,480
Stop it.

67
00:04:31,563 --> 00:04:33,648
(CREATURE RATTLING)

68
00:04:33,732 --> 00:04:35,776
What was that?

69
00:04:35,859 --> 00:04:37,652
What's on my back?

70
00:04:37,736 --> 00:04:40,447
What is it? What's on my back?

71
00:04:40,655 --> 00:04:45,535
Make the choice again,
Donna Noble, and change your mind.

72
00:04:45,619 --> 00:04:47,412
Turn right.

73
00:04:51,917 --> 00:04:53,877
I'm turning.

74
00:04:54,878 --> 00:04:56,671
Turn right.

75
00:04:57,672 --> 00:05:01,218
Turn right. Turn right.

76
00:05:02,552 --> 00:05:06,807
Let me tell you, sweetheart,
City executives don't need temps.

77
00:05:06,890 --> 00:05:08,892
Except for practice.

78
00:05:09,392 --> 00:05:12,521
Yeah. Suppose you're right.

79
00:05:12,813 --> 00:05:16,858
FORTUNE TELLER: 7urn right
and never meet that man.

80
00:05:16,942 --> 00:05:21,154
Turn right and change the world.

81
00:05:21,780 --> 00:05:23,907
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

82
00:06:00,610 --> 00:06:02,946
# We wish you a merry Christmas

83
00:06:03,071 --> 00:06:05,448
# We wish you a merry Christmas
We wish you a merry Christmas

84
00:06:05,574 --> 00:06:07,284
DONNA: Get out of the way.

85
00:06:07,409 --> 00:06:09,160
# And a happy New Year #

86
00:06:09,244 --> 00:06:11,037
DONNA: Get out of the way!

87
00:06:11,121 --> 00:06:12,914
(ALL CHEERING)

88
00:06:14,040 --> 00:06:16,543
Here we are. Feed at the trough.

89
00:06:16,626 --> 00:06:19,629
Mooky says let's go to the Boardwalk.
It's two-for-the-price-of-one.

90
00:06:19,754 --> 00:06:24,467
-Christmas Eve? It'll be heaving.
-Well, exactly. Get in and grab 'em.

91
00:06:24,593 --> 00:06:27,929
That's the second round of drinks
you've bought. It was my turn.

92
00:06:28,013 --> 00:06:30,599
I can afford it. Promotion.

93
00:06:30,682 --> 00:06:36,354
You are talking to Jival Chowdry's
Personal Assistant, I'll have you know.

94
00:06:36,438 --> 00:06:40,901
Capital P, capital A, £23,000 per annum.
Merci beaucoup!

95
00:06:40,984 --> 00:06:42,319
Here's to Mr Chowdry.

96
00:06:42,444 --> 00:06:44,571
ALL: Mr Chowdry.

97
00:06:44,654 --> 00:06:46,990
WOMAN: She gets all the luck.

98
00:06:47,073 --> 00:06:49,242
What's wrong? What is it?

99
00:06:49,326 --> 00:06:50,660
(RATTLING)

100
00:06:50,785 --> 00:06:52,871
-Sorry?
-Did someone spill a drink on me?

101
00:06:52,996 --> 00:06:54,205
No.

102
00:06:54,331 --> 00:06:57,334
Why do you keep looking
at my shoulder? What's wrong?

103
00:06:57,417 --> 00:06:58,501
I don't know.

104
00:06:58,585 --> 00:07:00,837
Don't tell me
you're getting all spooky again.

105
00:07:00,921 --> 00:07:02,923
It was bad enough when you saw
the ghost of Earl Mountbatten

106
00:07:03,006 --> 00:07:05,800
at the Boat Show.
What are you looking at?

107
00:07:05,884 --> 00:07:07,510
-What is it?
-It's like...

108
00:07:07,636 --> 00:07:09,054
(RATTLING)

109
00:07:09,137 --> 00:07:12,098
It's like there's something I can't see.

110
00:07:12,182 --> 00:07:15,352
MAN: No, shut up! All of you!
Come and see.

111
00:07:15,435 --> 00:07:17,729
Just look at the sky! It's a star!

112
00:07:17,854 --> 00:07:19,564
It's a Christmas star!

113
00:07:19,648 --> 00:07:21,399
Well, come on, then.

114
00:07:27,280 --> 00:07:30,158
-What the hell is that?
-Ken Livingston, that's what.

115
00:07:30,241 --> 00:07:33,495
Spending our money on decorations.
I mean, how much did that cost?

116
00:07:33,578 --> 00:07:37,082
Don't be so stupid.
It's flying, it's really flying!

117
00:07:41,795 --> 00:07:44,631
That's not a star, that's a web.

118
00:07:45,548 --> 00:07:47,634
It's headed east. Middle of the City.

119
00:07:47,717 --> 00:07:48,969
(RATTLING)

120
00:07:53,848 --> 00:07:55,600
(SCREAMING)

121
00:08:06,569 --> 00:08:10,323
Alice,
there's a great big web-star-thing

122
00:08:10,407 --> 00:08:13,076
shooting at people
and you're looking at me.

123
00:08:13,952 --> 00:08:16,663
There's something on your back.

124
00:08:21,626 --> 00:08:23,753
Donna! Where you going?

125
00:08:24,254 --> 00:08:28,008
You'll get yourself killed! Donna!

126
00:08:32,429 --> 00:08:33,847
Fire!

127
00:08:40,437 --> 00:08:44,190
MAN: Everyone stay back.
The Thames has been closed.

128
00:08:44,274 --> 00:08:45,525
Return to your homes.

129
00:08:45,608 --> 00:08:49,320
Keep away from the river,
and that's an order.

130
00:08:49,404 --> 00:08:50,864
(SIREN BLARING)

131
00:08:50,947 --> 00:08:55,035
ON RADIO: Trap 1 to Greyhound 15,
what is your report? Over.

132
00:08:55,118 --> 00:08:57,787
From the evidence,
I'd say he managed to stop the creature.

133
00:08:57,871 --> 00:08:59,748
Some sort of red spider.

134
00:08:59,831 --> 00:09:02,876
Blew up the base underneath the barrier,
flooded the whole thing. Over.

135
00:09:02,959 --> 00:09:05,420
And where is he now? Over.

136
00:09:06,838 --> 00:09:09,382
We've found a body, sir. Over.

137
00:09:09,924 --> 00:09:11,468
Is it him? Over.

138
00:09:11,593 --> 00:09:14,804
I think so.
He just didn't make it out in time.

139
00:09:19,893 --> 00:09:21,603
The Doctor is dead.

140
00:09:21,686 --> 00:09:25,023
It must have happened
too fast for him to regenerate.

141
00:09:31,196 --> 00:09:33,990
Escort the ambulance back to UNIT base.

142
00:09:45,085 --> 00:09:48,546
What happened? What did they find?
Sorry, did they find someone?

143
00:09:48,630 --> 00:09:52,258
I don't know.
Bloke called the Doctor or something.

144
00:09:52,342 --> 00:09:56,054
-Where is he?
-They took him away. He's dead.

145
00:09:58,890 --> 00:10:00,892
I'm sorry. Did you know him?

146
00:10:01,726 --> 00:10:05,271
I mean, they didn't say his name.

147
00:10:05,355 --> 00:10:07,357
It could be any doctor.

148
00:10:08,358 --> 00:10:10,276
I came so far.

149
00:10:12,362 --> 00:10:14,364
It could be anyone.

150
00:10:17,534 --> 00:10:19,661
-What's your name?
-Donna.

151
00:10:20,453 --> 00:10:21,830
And you?

152
00:10:21,913 --> 00:10:24,541
Oh, I was just passing by.

153
00:10:24,624 --> 00:10:27,502
I shouldn't even be here. This is wrong.

154
00:10:27,585 --> 00:10:30,088
This is wrong. This is so wrong.

155
00:10:30,171 --> 00:10:32,048
(RATTLING)

156
00:10:32,298 --> 00:10:35,802
-Sorry, what was it? Donna what?
-Why do you keep looking at my back?

157
00:10:35,885 --> 00:10:37,220
-I'm not.
-Yes, you are.

158
00:10:37,303 --> 00:10:39,764
You keep looking behind me.
You're doing it now.

159
00:10:39,848 --> 00:10:42,725
What is it? What's there?
Did someone put something on my back?

160
00:10:55,113 --> 00:10:56,865
You can't sack me!

161
00:10:56,948 --> 00:11:00,243
-I'm your personal assistant!
-You don't have to make a scene.

162
00:11:00,326 --> 00:11:03,163
Just come downstairs
and we can have a little talk.

163
00:11:03,246 --> 00:11:05,331
I'll make a scene, all right,
right in front of a tribunal.

164
00:11:05,415 --> 00:11:07,792
And the first thing I'm gonna say is
"Wandering hands!"

165
00:11:07,876 --> 00:11:09,419
Come on, Donna.
You know what it's been like

166
00:11:09,502 --> 00:11:11,713
for the past few months,
ever since that Christmas thing.

167
00:11:11,796 --> 00:11:13,923
Half my contracts were
on the other side of the river,

168
00:11:14,007 --> 00:11:15,842
and the Thames is still closed off.

169
00:11:15,925 --> 00:11:18,219
Look, I can't deliver.
I'm losing a fortune.

170
00:11:18,303 --> 00:11:20,555
Well, sack one of this lot! Sack cliff!

171
00:11:20,638 --> 00:11:23,892
He just sits there. I don't know
what he does all day. Sorry, cliff.

172
00:11:23,975 --> 00:11:26,853
Actually, I'm not sorry.
What do you do all day?

173
00:11:28,229 --> 00:11:29,480
What the hell?

174
00:11:29,564 --> 00:11:31,441
(GLASS SHATTERING)

175
00:11:35,653 --> 00:11:39,240
Like an earthquake. That's weird.

176
00:11:39,365 --> 00:11:42,327
Funny sort of clouds.

177
00:11:42,452 --> 00:11:47,665
Who typed this? I'm your PA.
Did you get someone else to type this?

178
00:11:50,543 --> 00:11:52,253
Beatrice!

179
00:11:53,463 --> 00:11:57,050
It sounds impossible,
but the entire hospital has vanished.

180
00:11:57,133 --> 00:11:59,510
The Royal Hope no longer exists.

181
00:11:59,594 --> 00:12:03,097
It's not been destroyed,
there's no wreckage, it's simply gone.

182
00:12:03,181 --> 00:12:05,141
Reports from bystanders say

183
00:12:05,225 --> 00:12:08,269
that the rain lifted up
around the hospital...

184
00:12:08,353 --> 00:12:11,940
Hole punch, having that. Stapler. Mine.

185
00:12:12,023 --> 00:12:15,360
Toy cactus, you can
have that, Beatrice. Catch.

186
00:12:15,443 --> 00:12:18,529
Cliff, I'd leave you my mouse mat,
but I'm worried you'd cut yourself.

187
00:12:18,613 --> 00:12:22,283
All right, Donna, have some respect.
There's 2,000 people in that hospital.

188
00:12:22,367 --> 00:12:24,327
-And it's vanished.
-I'll show you vanishing.

189
00:12:24,410 --> 00:12:26,496
Thanks for nothing!

190
00:12:26,579 --> 00:12:29,666
Oh, and you know when that money
went missing from the kitty?

191
00:12:29,749 --> 00:12:34,170
Anne Marie.
That's all I'm saying. Anne Marie!

192
00:12:34,295 --> 00:12:36,381
(CRASHING)

193
00:12:36,464 --> 00:12:39,467
Oh, don't tell me. The hospital's back.

194
00:12:39,550 --> 00:12:42,011
Well, isn't that wizard?

195
00:12:42,512 --> 00:12:47,016
To confirm, the Royal Hope Hospital
was returned to its original position,

196
00:12:47,100 --> 00:12:49,269
but with only one survivor.

197
00:12:49,352 --> 00:12:53,022
The only person left alive
ls medical student Oliver Morgenstern.

198
00:12:53,106 --> 00:12:55,441
...and there were these creatures.

199
00:12:55,525 --> 00:12:58,903
Like rhinos.
Talking rhinos in black leather.

200
00:12:58,987 --> 00:13:00,071
Rhinos?

201
00:13:00,154 --> 00:13:02,407
-Rhinos could be aliens.
-Shush.

202
00:13:03,032 --> 00:13:06,286
MORGENSTERN: We couldn't breathe,
we were running out of air.

203
00:13:06,369 --> 00:13:09,831
A colleague of mine gave me
the last oxygen tank.

204
00:13:09,914 --> 00:13:12,166
Martha. Martha Jones.

205
00:13:13,209 --> 00:13:14,961
And she died.

206
00:13:15,712 --> 00:13:18,172
Least you've got a hole punch.

207
00:13:18,631 --> 00:13:19,882
And a raffle ticket.

208
00:13:19,966 --> 00:13:23,720
Yeah, well, they can keep the raffle.
I wouldn't take a penny off that man.

209
00:13:23,803 --> 00:13:26,306
Honestly, you two.
There's aliens on the news.

210
00:13:26,389 --> 00:13:28,599
They took that hospital
all the way to the moon

211
00:13:28,683 --> 00:13:30,685
and you're banging on
about raffle tickets.

212
00:13:30,768 --> 00:13:34,314
Don't be daft, Gramps.
It wasn't the moon, it couldn't be.

213
00:13:34,397 --> 00:13:36,441
Yes, well, I am telling you,
it is getting worse.

214
00:13:36,524 --> 00:13:38,109
These past few years,

215
00:13:38,192 --> 00:13:40,987
it's like all of a sudden,
they suddenly know all about us.

216
00:13:41,070 --> 00:13:43,865
There's keen eyes up there
and they're watching us,

217
00:13:43,948 --> 00:13:45,158
and they're not friendly.

218
00:13:45,241 --> 00:13:46,868
This stapler says "Bea".

219
00:13:46,951 --> 00:13:49,245
Can't believe how well
you're taking it, me getting sacked.

220
00:13:49,329 --> 00:13:51,789
-Thought you'd hit the roof.
-I'm just tired, Donna.

221
00:13:51,914 --> 00:13:54,292
What with your father and everything.

222
00:13:54,375 --> 00:13:56,627
To be honest, I've given up on you.

223
00:13:56,753 --> 00:13:59,213
...this further report
Just in from Oliver Morgenstern.

224
00:13:59,297 --> 00:14:02,550
There was this woman who took control.
Said she knew what to do.

225
00:14:02,633 --> 00:14:05,219
Said she could stop the MRI
or something.

226
00:14:05,303 --> 00:14:08,514
Sarah Jane her name was.
Sarah Jane Smith.

227
00:14:08,598 --> 00:14:11,809
Sarah Jane Smith was a freelance
investigative journalist,

228
00:14:11,893 --> 00:14:14,187
formerly of Metropolitan Magazine.

229
00:14:14,270 --> 00:14:17,857
Her body was recovered
from the hospital late this afternoon.

230
00:14:18,441 --> 00:14:21,486
-What's for tea?
-I've got nothing in.

231
00:14:22,153 --> 00:14:26,991
I'll get chips. Last of my wages.
Fish and chips, yeah?

232
00:14:27,075 --> 00:14:31,037
...along with his teenage
friends Maria Jackson and Clyde Langer.

233
00:14:31,120 --> 00:14:33,539
It is feared that they also perished.

234
00:15:03,152 --> 00:15:06,072
DONNA: Blimey, you all right?

235
00:15:06,823 --> 00:15:08,574
What was that, fireworks?

236
00:15:08,658 --> 00:15:12,328
I dunno. I was just walking along.
That's weird.

237
00:15:14,497 --> 00:15:16,666
You're the one.

238
00:15:16,749 --> 00:15:19,168
Christmas Eve, I met you in town.

239
00:15:19,252 --> 00:15:22,046
-Donna, isn't it?
-What was your name?

240
00:15:22,171 --> 00:15:25,925
How're you doing? You're looking good.
How's things? What you been up to?

241
00:15:26,008 --> 00:15:27,510
You're doing it again.

242
00:15:27,635 --> 00:15:29,303
-What?
-Looking behind me.

243
00:15:29,387 --> 00:15:30,680
(RATTLING)

244
00:15:30,763 --> 00:15:33,891
People keep on doing that.
Looking at my back.

245
00:15:33,975 --> 00:15:35,768
What sort of people?

246
00:15:35,852 --> 00:15:38,312
People in the street. Strangers.

247
00:15:38,729 --> 00:15:41,691
I just catch them sometimes.
Staring at me.

248
00:15:42,567 --> 00:15:44,819
Like they're looking at something.

249
00:15:44,902 --> 00:15:48,239
And then I get home and I look
and there's nothing there.

250
00:15:48,322 --> 00:15:50,199
(RATTLING)

251
00:15:50,950 --> 00:15:53,995
-See, look? Now I'm doing it.
-What are you doing for Christmas?

252
00:15:54,078 --> 00:15:56,873
-What am I what?
-Next Christmas.

253
00:15:56,956 --> 00:15:59,709
-Any plans?
-I don't know. That's ages away.

254
00:15:59,792 --> 00:16:02,211
Nothing much, I suppose. Why?

255
00:16:03,045 --> 00:16:06,007
Just, I think you should get out,
you and your family.

256
00:16:06,090 --> 00:16:09,427
Don't stay in London.
Just leave the city.

257
00:16:09,510 --> 00:16:13,389
-What for?
-Nice hotel. Christmas break.

258
00:16:13,598 --> 00:16:14,807
Can't afford it.

259
00:16:14,891 --> 00:16:17,602
Well, no, you've got that raffle ticket.

260
00:16:17,685 --> 00:16:20,938
-How do you know about that?
-First prize.

261
00:16:21,022 --> 00:16:22,732
Luxury weekend break.

262
00:16:22,815 --> 00:16:25,568
Use it, Donna Noble.

263
00:16:25,735 --> 00:16:28,529
Why won't you tell me your name?

264
00:16:32,700 --> 00:16:35,203
I think you

265
00:16:35,286 --> 00:16:37,246
should leave me alone.

266
00:16:48,424 --> 00:16:52,178
(PLAYING ON CAR STEREO)
# ...a red-nosed reindeer... #

267
00:16:54,013 --> 00:16:57,016
GRANDDAD: Cor blimey,
that's what I call posh.

268
00:16:57,183 --> 00:17:01,270
I said you were lucky.
Didn't I always say? My lucky star.

269
00:17:01,896 --> 00:17:05,399
For God's sake, don't tell them
that we won it in a raffle. Be classy.

270
00:17:05,483 --> 00:17:08,444
-Dad, take those things off.
-No, I shan't. It's Christmas.

271
00:17:08,528 --> 00:17:11,155
Oi, I'll have that one, thank you.
It's got my liniment in it.

272
00:17:11,280 --> 00:17:15,451
I reckon we deserve this.
It's been a hell of a year.

273
00:17:15,535 --> 00:17:18,204
Your dad would've loved this.

274
00:17:18,287 --> 00:17:21,332
Yeah. He would've.

275
00:17:25,628 --> 00:17:27,296
(CHRISTMAS CAROL PLAYING)

276
00:17:27,421 --> 00:17:29,131
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

277
00:17:30,007 --> 00:17:33,469
Oi, Gramps, get that.
That'll be breakfast.

278
00:17:33,594 --> 00:17:37,306
-We've got croissants.
-Why can't you get it, Lady Muck?

279
00:17:37,390 --> 00:17:40,393
It's Christmas Day,
I never get up before ten.

280
00:17:40,476 --> 00:17:43,145
Only madam there
was up with the dawn chorus.

281
00:17:43,229 --> 00:17:45,231
Like when she was six years old.

282
00:17:45,314 --> 00:17:48,317
I'm not wasting a second in this place.

283
00:17:48,401 --> 00:17:50,903
-How was the sofa?
-Oh, yeah.

284
00:17:50,987 --> 00:17:53,531
Not so good, really. Oh, God...

285
00:17:53,656 --> 00:17:54,991
(GROANING)

286
00:17:55,116 --> 00:17:58,494
You know, we could've paid
for a second room.

287
00:17:58,578 --> 00:18:00,538
(WHISTLING) Oi!

288
00:18:00,621 --> 00:18:01,872
Merry Christmas.

289
00:18:01,956 --> 00:18:04,041
-Merry Christmas.
-Merry Christmas, Dad.

290
00:18:04,166 --> 00:18:05,585
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

291
00:18:05,668 --> 00:18:08,588
Yeah, all right.
Come on in, my darling. Grub's up.

292
00:18:08,671 --> 00:18:10,047
-Merry Christmas.
-Merry Christmas, sir.

293
00:18:10,131 --> 00:18:12,300
TV: We interrupt this programme
to bring you breaking news.

294
00:18:12,383 --> 00:18:13,551
SYLVIA: Have you seen this?

295
00:18:13,634 --> 00:18:15,928
DONNA: I thought nice early
breakfast, then we'll go for a walk.

296
00:18:16,012 --> 00:18:17,346
People always say that at Christmas,

297
00:18:17,430 --> 00:18:19,765
"Oh, we all went for a walk."”
I've always wanted to do that.

298
00:18:19,849 --> 00:18:22,893
So, walk first, presents later, yeah?

299
00:18:23,019 --> 00:18:24,437
Donna, come and see.

300
00:18:24,520 --> 00:18:26,522
(SPEAKING SPANISH)

301
00:18:26,606 --> 00:18:27,898
-What?
-Donna, look at the telly.

302
00:18:28,024 --> 00:18:29,358
(SPEAKING SPANISH)

303
00:18:29,525 --> 00:18:30,735
What does that mean?

304
00:18:30,818 --> 00:18:33,237
-I don't know what you're saying.
-Donna, look at the TV.

305
00:18:33,362 --> 00:18:35,573
(SPEAKING SPANISH)

306
00:18:35,656 --> 00:18:37,450
(RATTLING)

307
00:18:42,955 --> 00:18:45,666
For God's sake, Donna,
don't just stand there, come and look!

308
00:18:45,750 --> 00:18:49,879
...how this is possible,
but this footage is live and genuine.

309
00:18:49,962 --> 00:18:52,548
The object is falling on Central London.

310
00:18:52,632 --> 00:18:54,467
I repeat, this is not a hoax,

311
00:18:54,550 --> 00:18:57,803
a replica of the Titanic
is falling out of the sky

312
00:18:57,887 --> 00:19:00,431
and it's heading for Buckingham Palace.

313
00:19:00,556 --> 00:19:04,101
We're getting this footage
from the Guinevere range of satellites.

314
00:19:04,185 --> 00:19:06,729
Is that a film or something?

315
00:19:08,731 --> 00:19:11,484
The Royal Air Force
has declared an emer...

316
00:19:14,904 --> 00:19:16,405
(CRASHING)

317
00:19:22,244 --> 00:19:23,871
It's gone dead.

318
00:19:24,664 --> 00:19:27,416
-All of them.
-No, but the 7itanic?

319
00:19:27,500 --> 00:19:29,543
Oh, don't be daft.

320
00:19:30,419 --> 00:19:32,505
Is that like a sequel?

321
00:19:32,588 --> 00:19:34,507
Oh!

322
00:19:35,675 --> 00:19:37,885
Oh, God rest their souls.

323
00:19:37,968 --> 00:19:39,845
(RUMBLING)

324
00:19:43,766 --> 00:19:46,227
I was supposed to be out there
selling papers.

325
00:19:46,310 --> 00:19:48,270
I should've been there. We all should.

326
00:19:48,354 --> 00:19:49,855
We'd be dead.

327
00:19:50,690 --> 00:19:52,817
That's everyone.

328
00:19:52,900 --> 00:19:55,611
Every single person we know.

329
00:19:55,695 --> 00:19:57,697
The whole city.

330
00:19:58,447 --> 00:19:59,949
Can't be.

331
00:20:00,032 --> 00:20:02,827
But it is. It's gone.

332
00:20:02,910 --> 00:20:05,329
London's gone.

333
00:20:05,413 --> 00:20:07,832
If you hadn't won that raffle...

334
00:20:15,005 --> 00:20:18,175
Leeds? I'm not moving to Leeds!

335
00:20:18,259 --> 00:20:22,430
I'm afraid it's Leeds, or you can wait
in the hostel for another three months.

336
00:20:22,513 --> 00:20:23,973
All I want is a washing machine.

337
00:20:24,056 --> 00:20:26,809
What about Glasgow?
I heard there was jobs going in Glasgow.

338
00:20:26,892 --> 00:20:27,977
You can't pick and choose.

339
00:20:28,060 --> 00:20:30,980
We've the whole of southern England
flooded with radiation,

340
00:20:31,063 --> 00:20:33,774
seven million people
in need of relocation,

341
00:20:33,858 --> 00:20:38,571
and now France has closed its borders.
So it's Leeds or nothing. Next!

342
00:20:51,917 --> 00:20:55,171
SOLDIER ON MEGAPHONE: The Daniels
family, billeted at number 15.

343
00:20:55,337 --> 00:20:58,674
Mr and Mrs Obego, billeted at number 31.

344
00:20:58,758 --> 00:21:01,135
Miss Coltrane, you're in number 8.

345
00:21:01,218 --> 00:21:04,013
The Noble family, billeted at number 29.

346
00:21:04,096 --> 00:21:06,182
That's us. Come on, off we go.

347
00:21:07,349 --> 00:21:09,226
GRANDDAD: All right?

348
00:21:10,352 --> 00:21:13,022
Used to be a nice little family,
number 29.

349
00:21:13,105 --> 00:21:15,524
They missed one mortgage payment,
just one,

350
00:21:15,691 --> 00:21:18,027
they got booted out, all for you lot.

351
00:21:18,194 --> 00:21:20,821
Don't get all chippy with me,
Vera Duckworth.

352
00:21:20,905 --> 00:21:23,824
Pop your clogs on
and go and feed whippets.

353
00:21:23,908 --> 00:21:25,201
Sweetheart, come on.

354
00:21:25,284 --> 00:21:29,079
You're not gonna make the world
any better by shouting at it.

355
00:21:29,163 --> 00:21:31,040
I can try.

356
00:21:37,046 --> 00:21:38,881
What happens? Do we get keys?

357
00:21:38,964 --> 00:21:42,176
-I don't know, do I?
-Who do we ask, the soldiers?

358
00:21:43,052 --> 00:21:47,473
Hey! Is a big house. Room for all.

359
00:21:47,556 --> 00:21:50,643
-Welcome. In you come.
-I thought this was our house.

360
00:21:50,726 --> 00:21:54,897
Is many people's house. Is wonderful.
In, in, in.

361
00:21:56,106 --> 00:21:58,317
We been here for eight weeks already.

362
00:21:58,400 --> 00:22:01,946
I had a nice little paper shop
in Shepherd's Bush. All gone now.

363
00:22:02,029 --> 00:22:05,157
So, upstairs, we have
the Merchandani family,

364
00:22:05,241 --> 00:22:08,494
seven of them, good family, good kids.

365
00:22:08,577 --> 00:22:11,914
Except that one, be careful of him.

366
00:22:11,997 --> 00:22:14,542
I is joking!

367
00:22:14,625 --> 00:22:16,627
Where's that smile, eh?

368
00:22:17,253 --> 00:22:19,839
Rocco Colasanto. I'm here with my wife,

369
00:22:19,922 --> 00:22:23,008
and her sister and her husband and
their kids, and their daughter's kids.

370
00:22:23,092 --> 00:22:25,719
We've got the front room,
and my mother, she's got the back room.

371
00:22:25,803 --> 00:22:28,305
She's old, you forgive her.

372
00:22:28,430 --> 00:22:31,267
And this, this is you.

373
00:22:31,350 --> 00:22:34,436
This is your palazzo!

374
00:22:37,273 --> 00:22:40,609
-What do you mean, this is us?
-You live here.

375
00:22:40,693 --> 00:22:42,820
-We're living in the kitchen?
-You got camp beds.

376
00:22:42,945 --> 00:22:44,321
You got the cooker, you keep warm,

377
00:22:44,405 --> 00:22:46,699
you got the fridge, you keep cool.
Is good.

378
00:22:46,782 --> 00:22:49,326
-What about the bathroom?
-Nobody lives in the bathroom.

379
00:22:49,451 --> 00:22:51,453
No, I mean, is there a rota?

380
00:22:51,537 --> 00:22:54,331
(LAUGHING) Is pot luck. Is fun!

381
00:22:54,456 --> 00:22:57,459
I go wake Mama, she likes new people.

382
00:22:57,585 --> 00:23:01,130
Mama! Is people! Nice people!

383
00:23:03,299 --> 00:23:05,217
Ah, well.

384
00:23:05,301 --> 00:23:08,137
We'll settle in, won't we? Make do.

385
00:23:08,220 --> 00:23:10,389
Bit of wartime spirit, eh?

386
00:23:10,472 --> 00:23:13,976
But there isn't a war. There's no fight.

387
00:23:14,643 --> 00:23:16,312
There's just

388
00:23:16,812 --> 00:23:17,897
this.

389
00:23:17,980 --> 00:23:20,983
Well, America, they'll save us.
It was on the news.

390
00:23:21,108 --> 00:23:26,155
They're gonna send Great Britain
50 billion quid in financial aid.

391
00:23:26,238 --> 00:23:27,615
God bless America.

392
00:23:27,698 --> 00:23:32,828
America is in crisis
with over 60 million reported dead.

393
00:23:32,912 --> 00:23:35,789
Sixty million people
have dissolved into fat.

394
00:23:36,081 --> 00:23:37,833
And the fat is walking.

395
00:23:37,917 --> 00:23:42,004
People's fat has come to life
and is walking through the streets.

396
00:23:42,087 --> 00:23:43,839
And there are spaceships.

397
00:23:44,006 --> 00:23:47,968
There are reports of spaceships
over every major US city.

398
00:23:48,052 --> 00:23:51,138
-The fat is flying. It's leaving...
-Aliens.

399
00:23:52,181 --> 00:23:53,641
Yeah.

400
00:23:56,185 --> 00:23:59,855
Mary McGinty, do you remember her?

401
00:24:00,439 --> 00:24:01,857
Who was she?

402
00:24:01,982 --> 00:24:04,693
Worked in the newsagent's on a Sunday.

403
00:24:05,569 --> 00:24:07,529
Little woman, black hair.

404
00:24:08,697 --> 00:24:12,660
-Never really spoke to her.
-She'll be dead.

405
00:24:12,743 --> 00:24:16,705
Every day
I think of someone else. All dead.

406
00:24:16,789 --> 00:24:19,083
Maybe she went away for Christmas.

407
00:24:19,208 --> 00:24:20,501
Maybe.

408
00:24:22,211 --> 00:24:26,090
I'll go out tomorrow.
I'll walk into town.

409
00:24:26,173 --> 00:24:30,010
There's got to be work.
Everyone needs secretaries.

410
00:24:30,094 --> 00:24:33,305
Soon as I'm earning,
we'll get a proper place.

411
00:24:33,806 --> 00:24:35,516
Just you wait, Mum.

412
00:24:35,599 --> 00:24:39,311
-What if it never gets better?
-Of course it will.

413
00:24:39,395 --> 00:24:43,315
Even the bees are disappearing.
You don't see bumblebees any more.

414
00:24:43,399 --> 00:24:48,404
They'll sort us out,
the Emergency Government.

415
00:24:48,487 --> 00:24:51,573
-They'll do something.
-What if they don't?

416
00:24:52,241 --> 00:24:55,869
Then we'll complain.

417
00:24:55,953 --> 00:24:59,331
Who's gonna listen to us? Refugees.

418
00:24:59,915 --> 00:25:03,377
We haven't even got a vote.
We're just no one, Donna.

419
00:25:03,460 --> 00:25:04,753
(MEN SINGING)

420
00:25:04,837 --> 00:25:06,588
We don't exist.

421
00:25:06,672 --> 00:25:10,342
# And I spent all my money
on whisky and beer... #

422
00:25:10,426 --> 00:25:14,054
I am going to kill that man!

423
00:25:14,346 --> 00:25:16,306
(SINGING CONTINUES)

424
00:25:16,390 --> 00:25:19,059
Now listen, Mussolini!

425
00:25:19,893 --> 00:25:24,023
I am telling you for the last time
to button it!

426
00:25:24,106 --> 00:25:27,443
If I hear one more sea shanty...

427
00:25:30,779 --> 00:25:33,282
Always loved a sing-song.

428
00:25:33,615 --> 00:25:36,827
# I'm just a poor boy
and nobody loves me

429
00:25:36,910 --> 00:25:39,913
# He's just a poor boy
From a poor family

430
00:25:39,997 --> 00:25:42,750
# Spare him his life
from this monstrosity

431
00:25:44,543 --> 00:25:47,046
# Easy come, easy go
Will you let me go... #

432
00:25:47,129 --> 00:25:49,006
(MACHINE GUN FIRING)

433
00:25:51,133 --> 00:25:52,968
No, you stay here.

434
00:25:53,635 --> 00:25:54,928
Everyone, stay!

435
00:25:57,765 --> 00:26:00,851
Hey, firing at the car is not so good!

436
00:26:00,976 --> 00:26:02,811
You crazy or what?

437
00:26:02,895 --> 00:26:05,773
It's this ATMOS thing, it won't stop.
It's like gas, it's toxic.

438
00:26:05,856 --> 00:26:08,484
-Well, switch it off!
-I have done. It's still going.

439
00:26:08,567 --> 00:26:11,779
It's all the cars, every single
ATMOS car. They've gone mad.

440
00:26:11,862 --> 00:26:13,614
(RATTLING)

441
00:26:14,490 --> 00:26:17,493
You! Lady, turn round. Turn around!

442
00:26:17,576 --> 00:26:19,078
-A re you crazy, boy?
-Now! |

443
00:26:19,161 --> 00:26:21,955
-Put that gun down!
-I said, turn around!

444
00:26:22,039 --> 00:26:24,958
-Do what he says! Turn around!
-Show me your back!

445
00:26:25,042 --> 00:26:27,336
Now! Show me your back!

446
00:26:33,467 --> 00:26:37,054
-Sorry, I thought I saw...
-Call yourself a soldier?

447
00:26:37,137 --> 00:26:41,058
Pointing guns at innocent women.
You're a disgrace.

448
00:26:41,183 --> 00:26:43,936
In my day, we would have
had you court-martial led!

449
00:26:44,019 --> 00:26:47,940
Donna, where are you going?
It's not safe at night!

450
00:26:48,023 --> 00:26:50,150
Donna! Donna!

451
00:26:55,364 --> 00:26:56,615
Hello.

452
00:26:57,866 --> 00:26:59,243
Hi.

453
00:26:59,326 --> 00:27:01,453
It's the ATMOS devices.

454
00:27:01,537 --> 00:27:05,124
We're lucky, it's not so bad here,
Britain hasn't got that much petrol.

455
00:27:05,207 --> 00:27:07,376
But all over Europe,

456
00:27:07,459 --> 00:27:10,212
China, South Africa,

457
00:27:10,337 --> 00:27:13,132
they're getting choked by gas.

458
00:27:13,215 --> 00:27:16,301
-Can't anyone stop it?
-Yeah, they're trying right now.

459
00:27:16,385 --> 00:27:19,096
This little band of fighters,

460
00:27:19,221 --> 00:27:21,557
on board the Sontaran ship.

461
00:27:22,558 --> 00:27:24,893
Any second now.

462
00:27:39,658 --> 00:27:41,660
And that was...?

463
00:27:41,743 --> 00:27:44,037
That was the Torchwood team.

464
00:27:44,121 --> 00:27:47,916
Gwen Cooper,
Ianto Jones, they gave their lives.

465
00:27:48,792 --> 00:27:52,713
And Captain Jack Harkness has
transported to the Sontaran homeworld.

466
00:27:52,796 --> 00:27:54,882
There's no one left.

467
00:27:57,092 --> 00:27:59,595
You're always wearing the same clothes.

468
00:27:59,720 --> 00:28:01,555
Why won't you tell me your name?

469
00:28:01,638 --> 00:28:04,433
None of this was meant to happen.

470
00:28:05,642 --> 00:28:07,853
There was a man,

471
00:28:07,936 --> 00:28:10,939
this wonderful man, and he stopped it.

472
00:28:11,023 --> 00:28:15,319
The Titanic, the Adipose, the ATMOS,
he stopped them all from happening.

473
00:28:15,444 --> 00:28:17,070
That doctor?

474
00:28:17,946 --> 00:28:19,990
-You knew him.
-Did I?

475
00:28:21,283 --> 00:28:24,286
-When?
-I think you dream about him sometimes.

476
00:28:24,411 --> 00:28:25,871
It's a man in a suit.

477
00:28:25,954 --> 00:28:29,541
Tall, thin man. Great hair.

478
00:28:29,625 --> 00:28:32,419
Some really great hair.

479
00:28:33,253 --> 00:28:36,423
-Who are you?
-I was like you.

480
00:28:36,506 --> 00:28:39,760
I used to be you.
'Cause you've travelled with him, Donna,

481
00:28:39,843 --> 00:28:41,803
you travelled with the Doctor
in a different world.

482
00:28:41,887 --> 00:28:44,223
I never met him. And he's dead.

483
00:28:44,306 --> 00:28:46,642
He died underneath the Thames
on Christmas Eve.

484
00:28:46,725 --> 00:28:48,185
But you were meant to be there.

485
00:28:48,310 --> 00:28:51,772
He needed someone to stop him,
and that was you. You made him leave.

486
00:28:51,897 --> 00:28:53,649
You saved his life.

487
00:28:57,152 --> 00:28:58,654
(SCREAMING)

488
00:29:01,531 --> 00:29:04,743
Doctor, you can stop now.

489
00:29:05,577 --> 00:29:08,413
Stop it! I don't know what
you're talking about. Leave me alone.

490
00:29:08,497 --> 00:29:11,583
Something is coming, Donna.
Something worse.

491
00:29:11,667 --> 00:29:14,795
The whole world is stinking.

492
00:29:14,878 --> 00:29:17,297
How could anything be worse than this?

493
00:29:17,381 --> 00:29:20,842
Trust me. We need the Doctor
more than ever. I've...

494
00:29:20,926 --> 00:29:23,762
I've been pulled across
from a different universe

495
00:29:23,845 --> 00:29:26,098
because every
single universe is in danger.

496
00:29:26,181 --> 00:29:28,141
It's coming, Donna.

497
00:29:28,225 --> 00:29:31,603
It's coming from across the stars
and nothing can stop it.

498
00:29:31,687 --> 00:29:33,855
What is?

499
00:29:33,939 --> 00:29:35,607
The darkness.

500
00:29:36,900 --> 00:29:39,778
Well, what do you keep telling me for?

501
00:29:39,903 --> 00:29:42,197
What am I supposed to do?

502
00:29:42,281 --> 00:29:45,075
I'm nothing special. I mean, I'm...

503
00:29:45,200 --> 00:29:48,370
I'm not...I'm nothing special.
I'm a temp.

504
00:29:48,453 --> 00:29:50,914
I'm not even that. I'm nothing.

505
00:29:51,039 --> 00:29:55,168
Donna Noble, you're the most important
woman in the whole of creation.

506
00:29:56,878 --> 00:29:58,797
Oh, don't.

507
00:29:58,880 --> 00:30:01,550
Just don't.

508
00:30:03,552 --> 00:30:05,721
I'm tired.

509
00:30:06,263 --> 00:30:09,182
I'm so tired.

510
00:30:10,767 --> 00:30:13,186
I need you to come with me.

511
00:30:13,312 --> 00:30:16,189
Yeah, well.

512
00:30:16,273 --> 00:30:19,484
Blonde hair might work on the men,
but you ain't shifting me, lady.

513
00:30:19,568 --> 00:30:21,570
That's more like it.

514
00:30:21,695 --> 00:30:23,488
I've got plenty more.

515
00:30:23,572 --> 00:30:25,490
But you'll come with me.

516
00:30:25,574 --> 00:30:27,242
Only when you want to.

517
00:30:27,367 --> 00:30:30,203
-You'll have a long wait, then.
-Not really, just three weeks.

518
00:30:30,287 --> 00:30:33,749
Tell me, does your grandfather
still own that telescope?

519
00:30:35,417 --> 00:30:37,169
He never lets go of it.

520
00:30:37,252 --> 00:30:39,254
Three weeks' time.

521
00:30:40,005 --> 00:30:41,840
But you've got to be certain.

522
00:30:41,923 --> 00:30:46,762
'Cause when you come with me, Donna,
I'm sorry, so sorry, but

523
00:30:48,930 --> 00:30:51,099
you're going to die.

524
00:31:07,282 --> 00:31:08,367
(WHOOPING)

525
00:31:08,450 --> 00:31:11,078
And you! I'm gonna miss you most of all.

526
00:31:11,203 --> 00:31:14,081
All flame-haired and fiery.

527
00:31:14,164 --> 00:31:16,458
Oh, but why do you have to go?

528
00:31:16,541 --> 00:31:20,003
Is the new law.
England for the English, et cetera.

529
00:31:20,128 --> 00:31:22,464
They can't send us home,
the oceans are closed.

530
00:31:22,589 --> 00:31:24,299
They build lab our camps.

531
00:31:24,383 --> 00:31:27,803
I know, but lab our doing what?
There aren't any jobs.

532
00:31:27,928 --> 00:31:31,014
Sewing, digging, is good.

533
00:31:31,139 --> 00:31:34,976
Now, stop it before I kiss you too much.

534
00:31:36,978 --> 00:31:38,647
Wilfred.

535
00:31:38,730 --> 00:31:40,607
My capitano.

536
00:31:56,540 --> 00:32:00,919
DONNA: It'll be quiet with him gone.
Still, we'll have more room.

537
00:32:01,002 --> 00:32:03,088
Labour camps.

538
00:32:03,171 --> 00:32:05,590
That's what they called them last time.

539
00:32:05,715 --> 00:32:07,426
What do you mean?

540
00:32:12,055 --> 00:32:13,932
It's happening again.

541
00:32:14,015 --> 00:32:15,559
What is?

542
00:32:21,356 --> 00:32:24,776
Excuse me.
Excuse me, where are you taking them?

543
00:32:24,860 --> 00:32:28,780
Where are you going?
Where are you going?

544
00:32:28,864 --> 00:32:30,866
Where are you going?

545
00:32:31,616 --> 00:32:34,286
Where are you going!

546
00:32:53,013 --> 00:32:56,558
I asked about jobs, with the army.

547
00:32:56,933 --> 00:32:59,227
They said I wasn't qualified.

548
00:33:03,315 --> 00:33:04,649
You were right.

549
00:33:04,733 --> 00:33:07,903
You said I should have
worked harder at school.

550
00:33:13,158 --> 00:33:15,994
I suppose I've always been
a disappointment.

551
00:33:16,077 --> 00:33:17,579
Yeah.

552
00:33:33,094 --> 00:33:35,805
You know, we'd get a bit of cash
if we sold this thing.

553
00:33:35,931 --> 00:33:37,182
Don't you dare.

554
00:33:38,642 --> 00:33:42,229
I always imagined your old age,

555
00:33:42,312 --> 00:33:44,356
I'd have put a bit of money by.

556
00:33:44,439 --> 00:33:46,775
Make you comfy.

557
00:33:46,858 --> 00:33:48,693
Never did.

558
00:33:48,777 --> 00:33:50,612
I'm just useless.

559
00:33:54,282 --> 00:33:57,410
You're supposed to say,
"No, you're not."

560
00:33:57,494 --> 00:34:00,080
-Ah, it must be the alignment.
-What's wrong?

561
00:34:00,163 --> 00:34:03,625
Well, I dunno. It can't be the lens
"cause I was looking at Orion.

562
00:34:03,708 --> 00:34:05,877
The constellation of Orion.

563
00:34:05,961 --> 00:34:09,047
You take a look.
Now tell me, what can you see?

564
00:34:09,130 --> 00:34:12,217
-Where?
-Well, up there, in the sky.

565
00:34:14,135 --> 00:34:16,596
Well, I can't see anything.
It's just black.

566
00:34:16,680 --> 00:34:19,558
Well, I mean, it's working.
The telescope is working.

567
00:34:19,641 --> 00:34:21,977
Well, maybe it's clouds.

568
00:34:22,102 --> 00:34:24,229
-There is no clouds.
-Well, there must be.

569
00:34:24,312 --> 00:34:27,190
There's not. It was there.

570
00:34:27,315 --> 00:34:30,151
An entire constellation.

571
00:34:32,362 --> 00:34:33,572
Look!

572
00:34:34,531 --> 00:34:36,324
Look there.

573
00:34:37,784 --> 00:34:39,578
They're going out.

574
00:34:39,703 --> 00:34:41,580
Oh, my God!

575
00:34:41,663 --> 00:34:45,166
Donna, look, the stars are going out.

576
00:34:53,592 --> 00:34:54,968
I'm ready.

577
00:35:13,528 --> 00:35:16,448
VOICE ON PA:
Lodestone testing now at 15.4.

578
00:35:16,531 --> 00:35:19,034
Repeat, 15.4.

579
00:35:21,202 --> 00:35:23,955
-Ma'am.
-ROSE: I've told you, don't salute.

580
00:35:24,039 --> 00:35:26,499
Well, if you're not
going to tell us your name.

581
00:35:26,583 --> 00:35:28,043
DONNA: You don't know either?

582
00:35:28,168 --> 00:35:31,129
I've crossed too many different
realities, trust me, the wrong word

583
00:35:31,212 --> 00:35:34,633
in the wrong place
can change an entire causal nexus.

584
00:35:34,716 --> 00:35:37,010
She talks like that. A lot.

585
00:35:37,844 --> 00:35:41,389
-And you must be Miss Noble.
-Donna.

586
00:35:41,723 --> 00:35:44,559
Captain Erisa Magambo.
Thank you for this.

587
00:35:44,684 --> 00:35:46,895
-I don't even know what I'm doing.
-Is it awake?

588
00:35:46,978 --> 00:35:49,981
Seems to be quiet today. Ticking over.

589
00:35:50,065 --> 00:35:51,900
Like it's waiting.

590
00:35:52,317 --> 00:35:54,235
Do you want to see it?

591
00:35:55,487 --> 00:35:57,280
What's a police box?

592
00:35:57,364 --> 00:35:59,991
They salvaged it from underneath
the Thames. Just go inside.

593
00:36:00,075 --> 00:36:02,327
-What for?
-Just go in.

594
00:36:21,262 --> 00:36:23,515
DONNA: No way!

595
00:36:25,058 --> 00:36:27,310
(CHUCKLING)

596
00:36:56,256 --> 00:36:57,966
What do you think?

597
00:36:59,968 --> 00:37:01,636
Can I have a coffee?

598
00:37:01,720 --> 00:37:04,472
Time And Relative Dimension in Space.

599
00:37:05,348 --> 00:37:09,436
This room used to shine with light.
I think it's dying.

600
00:37:12,772 --> 00:37:14,983
(HUMMING)

601
00:37:15,108 --> 00:37:17,402
It's still trying to help.

602
00:37:17,485 --> 00:37:21,740
-And it belonged to the Doctor?
-He was a Time Lord.

603
00:37:21,865 --> 00:37:23,158
Last of his kind.

604
00:37:23,283 --> 00:37:27,162
But if he was so special,
what was he doing with me?

605
00:37:27,328 --> 00:37:29,038
He thought you were brilliant.

606
00:37:29,164 --> 00:37:31,166
-Don't be stupid.
-But you are.

607
00:37:31,291 --> 00:37:34,711
It just took the Doctor to show
you that, simply by being with him.

608
00:37:34,836 --> 00:37:38,006
He did the same to me,
to everyone he touches.

609
00:37:40,675 --> 00:37:42,635
Were you and him...

610
00:37:49,434 --> 00:37:51,269
(RATTLING)

611
00:37:52,771 --> 00:37:55,064
-Do you want to see it?
-No.

612
00:37:58,610 --> 00:37:59,819
Go on, then.

613
00:38:00,278 --> 00:38:02,071
We don't know how the Tardis works,

614
00:38:02,155 --> 00:38:04,449
but we've managed to scrape off
the surface technology.

615
00:38:04,532 --> 00:38:06,826
Enough to show you the creature.

616
00:38:07,577 --> 00:38:10,121
-It's a creature?
-Just stand here.

617
00:38:10,205 --> 00:38:12,207
Out of the circle, please.

618
00:38:13,291 --> 00:38:15,627
Yes, ma'am.

619
00:38:15,710 --> 00:38:17,712
Can't you stay with me?

620
00:38:18,546 --> 00:38:20,131
Ready?

621
00:38:20,215 --> 00:38:22,383
And activate.

622
00:38:29,724 --> 00:38:31,226
Open your eyes, Donna.

623
00:38:31,309 --> 00:38:34,270
-Is it there?
-Open your eyes. Look at it.

624
00:38:35,396 --> 00:38:38,149
-I can't.
-It's part of you, Donna. Look.

625
00:38:38,233 --> 00:38:40,318
(CREATURE RATTLING)

626
00:38:47,951 --> 00:38:50,078
It's okay, it's okay,
it's okay, calm down.

627
00:38:50,161 --> 00:38:52,956
Donna, Donna, Donna! Okay.

628
00:38:54,707 --> 00:38:57,335
(CREATURE RATTLING)

629
00:39:04,759 --> 00:39:07,595
-What is it?
-We don't know.

630
00:39:07,679 --> 00:39:10,431
Oh, thanks.

631
00:39:10,515 --> 00:39:12,475
It feeds off time.

632
00:39:12,600 --> 00:39:15,603
By changing time, by making
someone's life take a different turn.

633
00:39:15,728 --> 00:39:19,941
Like meetings never made.

634
00:39:20,024 --> 00:39:21,818
Children never born.

635
00:39:21,901 --> 00:39:23,778
A life never loved.

636
00:39:24,571 --> 00:39:26,030
But with you it's...

637
00:39:26,114 --> 00:39:28,783
-But I never did anything important.
-Yeah, you did.

638
00:39:28,950 --> 00:39:31,703
One day that thing made you turn right
instead of left.

639
00:39:31,786 --> 00:39:33,621
-When was that?
-You wouldn't remember.

640
00:39:33,788 --> 00:39:35,290
It was the most ordinary day
in the world.

641
00:39:35,373 --> 00:39:38,209
But by turning right,
you never met the Doctor

642
00:39:38,293 --> 00:39:41,546
and the whole world
just changed around you.

643
00:39:41,629 --> 00:39:43,548
Can you get rid of it?

644
00:39:43,631 --> 00:39:45,466
I can't even touch it.

645
00:39:46,634 --> 00:39:48,970
Seems to be in a state of flux.

646
00:39:49,095 --> 00:39:51,848
What does that mean?

647
00:39:51,931 --> 00:39:55,560
I don't know.
Sort of thing the Doctor would say.

648
00:39:55,643 --> 00:39:57,770
You liar!

649
00:39:58,354 --> 00:40:01,149
You told me I was special!

650
00:40:01,274 --> 00:40:03,651
But it's not me, it's this thing!

651
00:40:03,776 --> 00:40:05,486
I'm just a host!

652
00:40:05,570 --> 00:40:07,822
No, there's more than that.

653
00:40:08,323 --> 00:40:10,158
The readings are strange.

654
00:40:10,241 --> 00:40:12,452
It's like reality is just bending
around you.

655
00:40:12,535 --> 00:40:14,662
Because of this thing!

656
00:40:14,746 --> 00:40:17,415
No, no, we're getting
separate readings from you.

657
00:40:17,498 --> 00:40:20,084
And they've always been there,
since the day you were born.

658
00:40:20,168 --> 00:40:22,879
This is not relevant to the mission.

659
00:40:22,962 --> 00:40:25,548
I thought it was just
the Doctor we needed,

660
00:40:25,632 --> 00:40:27,258
but it's the both of you.

661
00:40:27,342 --> 00:40:30,261
The Doctor and Donna Noble. Together.

662
00:40:30,345 --> 00:40:32,931
To stop the stars from going out.

663
00:40:33,014 --> 00:40:34,641
Why?

664
00:40:35,516 --> 00:40:37,852
What can I do?

665
00:40:41,606 --> 00:40:43,733
(CREATURE RATTLING)

666
00:40:44,150 --> 00:40:46,110
Turn it off.

667
00:40:47,195 --> 00:40:48,529
-Please.
-Captain.

668
00:40:48,613 --> 00:40:50,031
Power down.

669
00:40:58,873 --> 00:41:00,291
It's

670
00:41:00,375 --> 00:41:02,377
still there, though.

671
00:41:03,544 --> 00:41:05,630
What can I do

672
00:41:05,713 --> 00:41:08,049
to get rid of it?

673
00:41:08,132 --> 00:41:09,884
You're going to travel in time.

674
00:41:09,968 --> 00:41:12,178
The Tardis has tracked down
the moment of intervention,

675
00:41:12,261 --> 00:41:14,555
Monday 25th,
one minute past ten in the morning.

676
00:41:14,681 --> 00:41:17,266
Your car was on Little Sutton Street,
leading to the Eating Road,

677
00:41:17,392 --> 00:41:19,102
but you turned right,
heading towards Griffin's Parade.

678
00:41:19,185 --> 00:41:21,062
You need to turn left.
That's the most important thing.

679
00:41:21,187 --> 00:41:22,855
You've got to go back, turn left.

680
00:41:22,939 --> 00:41:24,899
Have you got that, Donna?
One minute past ten,

681
00:41:24,983 --> 00:41:27,443
make yourself turn left,
heading for the Chiswick High Road.

682
00:41:27,527 --> 00:41:28,778
Keep the jacket on at all times.

683
00:41:28,861 --> 00:41:30,822
It's insulation
against temporal feedback.

684
00:41:30,905 --> 00:41:33,366
This will correspond to local time
wherever you land.

685
00:41:33,449 --> 00:41:35,743
This is to combat dehydration.

686
00:41:45,753 --> 00:41:47,380
This is where we leave you.

687
00:41:47,463 --> 00:41:48,965
I don't want to see that thing
on my back.

688
00:41:49,090 --> 00:41:51,259
No, the mirrors are just incidental.

689
00:41:51,342 --> 00:41:53,302
They bounce Chronon Energy
back into the centre

690
00:41:53,386 --> 00:41:56,681
which we control
and decide the destination.

691
00:41:56,764 --> 00:41:58,558
It's a time machine.

692
00:41:58,933 --> 00:42:00,643
It's a time machine.

693
00:42:00,727 --> 00:42:02,562
If you could.

694
00:42:08,735 --> 00:42:10,069
Powering up.

695
00:42:15,575 --> 00:42:18,119
-How do you know it's gonna work?
-Hmm?

696
00:42:18,244 --> 00:42:20,621
Oh, yeah, we don't.

697
00:42:20,705 --> 00:42:23,374
We're just guessing.

698
00:42:25,668 --> 00:42:27,045
Brilliant.

699
00:42:27,128 --> 00:42:29,172
Just remember,
when you get to the junction,

700
00:42:29,255 --> 00:42:32,133
change the car's direction
by one minute past ten.

701
00:42:32,216 --> 00:42:34,469
-How do I do that?
-That's up to you.

702
00:42:34,635 --> 00:42:35,803
Well...

703
00:42:35,887 --> 00:42:39,557
I'll just have to run up to myself,

704
00:42:39,640 --> 00:42:41,726
and have a good argument.

705
00:42:41,809 --> 00:42:43,394
I'd like to see that.

706
00:42:43,478 --> 00:42:45,438
Activate lodestone.

707
00:42:47,982 --> 00:42:49,692
Good luck.

708
00:42:49,776 --> 00:42:52,153
-I'm ready.
-One minute past ten.

709
00:42:52,236 --> 00:42:54,530
'Cause I understand now.

710
00:42:54,614 --> 00:42:59,243
You said I was gonna die,
but you mean this whole world

711
00:42:59,327 --> 00:43:01,746
is gonna blink out of existence.

712
00:43:01,829 --> 00:43:03,664
But that's not dying,

713
00:43:03,748 --> 00:43:06,417
"cause a better world takes its place.

714
00:43:06,501 --> 00:43:08,377
The Doctor's world.

715
00:43:08,461 --> 00:43:10,338
And I'm still alive.

716
00:43:12,173 --> 00:43:14,342
That's right, isn't it? I don't die.

717
00:43:14,425 --> 00:43:18,387
If I change things, I don't die.
That's right, isn't it?

718
00:43:23,601 --> 00:43:25,144
I'm sorry.

719
00:43:25,228 --> 00:43:26,854
But I can't die.

720
00:43:28,272 --> 00:43:29,857
I've got a future.

721
00:43:30,691 --> 00:43:34,320
With the Doctor. You told me.

722
00:43:34,403 --> 00:43:36,239
Activate!

723
00:43:56,467 --> 00:43:58,803
(RADIO PLAYING UPBEAT MUSIC)

724
00:44:06,686 --> 00:44:08,479
(CHEERING)

725
00:44:13,234 --> 00:44:14,944
Hold on.

726
00:44:15,069 --> 00:44:17,280
But this is...I'm not...

727
00:44:18,948 --> 00:44:21,242
This is Sutton Court.

728
00:44:21,826 --> 00:44:26,330
I'm half a mile away.
I'm half a mile away!

729
00:44:29,083 --> 00:44:30,626
Four minutes.

730
00:44:31,669 --> 00:44:33,588
Oh, my God.

731
00:44:35,840 --> 00:44:37,466
(DONNA PANTING)

732
00:44:37,550 --> 00:44:39,385
Jival Chowdry.

733
00:44:40,386 --> 00:44:42,513
He runs that little photocopy business

734
00:44:42,597 --> 00:44:45,349
in Merchant Street
and he needs a secretary.

735
00:44:45,433 --> 00:44:47,852
I've got a job.

736
00:44:48,769 --> 00:44:50,771
(DONNA PANTING)

737
00:44:55,443 --> 00:44:58,112
HC Clements is in the City.

738
00:44:58,196 --> 00:45:02,116
It's nice, it's posh, so stop it.

739
00:45:05,203 --> 00:45:07,163
(BEEPING)

740
00:45:12,752 --> 00:45:15,546
It won't take long, just turn right.

741
00:45:17,715 --> 00:45:21,510
I'm going left.
If you don't like it, get out and walk.

742
00:45:22,762 --> 00:45:24,347
You think I'm so useless.

743
00:45:24,430 --> 00:45:27,808
Oh, I know why you want
a job with HC Clements, lady.

744
00:45:27,892 --> 00:45:29,685
'Cause you think you'll meet a man.

745
00:45:32,313 --> 00:45:34,690
How long...How long...

746
00:45:37,401 --> 00:45:39,904
I'm not gonna get there.

747
00:45:44,659 --> 00:45:47,036
You're gonna die.

748
00:45:53,709 --> 00:45:57,964
City executives don't need temps.
Except for practice.

749
00:45:58,673 --> 00:46:00,091
Yeah.

750
00:46:00,174 --> 00:46:02,218
I suppose you're right.

751
00:46:06,889 --> 00:46:08,766
Please.

752
00:46:10,559 --> 00:46:12,103
(TYRES SCREECHING)

753
00:46:15,606 --> 00:46:17,608
Can you hear that?

754
00:46:18,025 --> 00:46:21,279
-Hold on. Back up.
-0}, get a move on!

755
00:46:22,738 --> 00:46:26,158
-The traffic's stopping.
-Something must've happened.

756
00:46:36,669 --> 00:46:38,254
Tell him this.

757
00:46:38,754 --> 00:46:40,131
Two words.

758
00:46:51,392 --> 00:46:54,395
Well, that decides it.
I'm not sitting in a traffic jam.

759
00:46:54,520 --> 00:46:56,814
(ECHOING) I'm going left.

760
00:46:59,025 --> 00:47:05,239
(ECHOING) Left left left...

761
00:47:18,627 --> 00:47:22,882
-What the hell is that?
-You were so strong.

762
00:47:23,924 --> 00:47:26,177
What are you?

763
00:47:26,260 --> 00:47:28,471
What will you be?

764
00:47:29,430 --> 00:47:32,058
What will you be?

765
00:47:34,560 --> 00:47:36,479
Everything all right?

766
00:47:36,604 --> 00:47:39,190
Oh, God!

767
00:47:39,273 --> 00:47:42,109
(CHUCKLING) What's that for?

768
00:47:42,568 --> 00:47:44,236
I don't know.

769
00:47:51,827 --> 00:47:53,829
I can't remember.

770
00:47:54,580 --> 00:47:56,582
It's slipping away.

771
00:47:57,458 --> 00:48:01,295
You know like when you try and think
of a dream and it sort of goes.

772
00:48:01,420 --> 00:48:05,466
Just got lucky, this thing.
It's one of the Trickster's Brigade.

773
00:48:05,591 --> 00:48:08,094
It changes a life in tiny little ways.

774
00:48:08,177 --> 00:48:11,555
Most times the universe just
compensates around it, but with you...

775
00:48:11,639 --> 00:48:14,308
Great big parallel world.

776
00:48:15,059 --> 00:48:18,145
Hold on, you said parallel worlds
were sealed off.

777
00:48:18,229 --> 00:48:21,190
They are.
But you had one created around you.

778
00:48:22,233 --> 00:48:24,652
Funny thing is,
seems to be happening a lot.

779
00:48:24,735 --> 00:48:26,487
To you.

780
00:48:26,612 --> 00:48:29,657
-How do you mean?
-Well, the Library and then this.

781
00:48:30,366 --> 00:48:34,078
Just goes with the job, I suppose.

782
00:48:34,161 --> 00:48:37,415
Sometimes I think there's way too much
coincidence around you, Donna.

783
00:48:37,498 --> 00:48:39,291
I met you once.
Then I met your grandfather.

784
00:48:39,375 --> 00:48:40,960
Then I met you again.

785
00:48:41,043 --> 00:48:44,505
In the whole wide universe,
I met you for a second time.

786
00:48:45,673 --> 00:48:48,968
It's like something's
binding us together.

787
00:48:49,051 --> 00:48:50,428
Don't be so daft.

788
00:48:50,511 --> 00:48:54,098
-I'm nothing special.
-Yes, you are, you're brilliant.

789
00:48:55,141 --> 00:48:57,101
He thought you were brilliant.

790
00:48:58,686 --> 00:49:00,479
She said that.

791
00:49:01,021 --> 00:49:02,857
-Who did?
-That woman.

792
00:49:04,024 --> 00:49:07,111
-I can't remember.
-Well, she never existed now.

793
00:49:07,194 --> 00:49:10,197
No, but she said the stars...

794
00:49:12,992 --> 00:49:15,911
-She said the stars are going out.
-Yeah, but that world's gone.

795
00:49:15,995 --> 00:49:20,082
No, but she said it was all worlds.
Every world.

796
00:49:20,541 --> 00:49:24,128
She said the darkness is coming.
Even here.

797
00:49:24,211 --> 00:49:26,172
-Who was she?
-I don't know.

798
00:49:26,547 --> 00:49:28,549
What did she look like?

799
00:49:28,674 --> 00:49:30,384
She was...

800
00:49:31,177 --> 00:49:33,137
-Blonde.
-What was her name?

801
00:49:33,220 --> 00:49:35,931
-I don't know.
-Donna, what was her name?

802
00:49:37,892 --> 00:49:40,644
But she told me to warn you.

803
00:49:41,312 --> 00:49:43,147
She said, "Two words."

804
00:49:43,230 --> 00:49:46,108
What two words? What were they?
What did she say?

805
00:49:51,739 --> 00:49:53,491
Bad wolf.

806
00:49:55,326 --> 00:49:57,077
What does it mean?

807
00:50:20,142 --> 00:50:23,521
Doctor, what is it? What's bad wolf?

808
00:50:23,604 --> 00:50:24,980
(CLOISTER BELL TOLLING)

809
00:50:25,064 --> 00:50:26,941
It's the end of the universe.

810
00:50:40,788 --> 00:50:43,457
Ladies and gentlemen, we are at war.

811
00:50:43,541 --> 00:50:46,001
-It can't be.
-There's nothing I can do.

812
00:50:46,085 --> 00:50:47,419
Oh, my God!

813
00:50:47,503 --> 00:50:49,338
What is it? Who are they?

814
00:50:49,421 --> 00:50:51,131
What are we going to do?

815
00:50:51,674 --> 00:50:54,760
-It's impossible.
-It can't be.

816
00:50:54,843 --> 00:50:56,679
I'm sorry, we're dead.

817
00:50:56,762 --> 00:50:58,556
Doctor, come back!

818
00:50:58,639 --> 00:51:00,015
(MECHANICAL LAUGHING)

819
00:51:00,099 --> 00:51:01,225
It's only just beginning.

